# Next.js Frontend Rules

## Core principles
- Use Next.js App Router (not Pages Router).
- Use TypeScript strictly (no `any`).
- Prefer functional and declarative programming.
- Avoid classes except for React error boundaries.
- Use hooks and functions.

## Project structure
- `src/app/` — routes, layouts, thin `page.tsx` files
- `src/components/ui/` — primitives
- `src/components/shared/` — shell, providers, feature views
- `src/hooks/` — TanStack Query hooks and reusable logic
- `src/services/` — HTTP client and API functions (no direct calls from UI)
- `src/store/` — Zustand global state
- `src/utils/` — pure helpers
- `src/schemas/` — Zod validation schemas

## Naming
- camelCase — variables and functions
- PascalCase — components
- kebab-case — folders
- Prefix event handlers with `handle` (e.g. `handleSubmit`)
- Booleans — `isLoading`, `hasError`, `isOpen`

## Components
- Small, reusable pieces; one main component per file.
- Prefer named exports.
- Avoid prop drilling — use Zustand or composition.

## Styling
- Tailwind CSS, mobile-first.
- Avoid inline styles except unavoidable (e.g. third-party chart).

## State
- Local — `useState` / `useReducer`
- Global — Zustand (`src/store/`)
- Server/async — TanStack Query (`src/hooks/`)

## API
- Centralized in `src/services/`.
- UI and route views consume data via hooks only.

## Errors
- Use error boundaries (`RootErrorBoundary`).
- User-facing copy via toasts and inline messages.

## Performance
- Default to Server Components in `page.tsx` where possible.
- Use `"use client"` only in views/hooks that need it.
- Lazy-load heavy client modules when justified.

## Security
- No secrets in the frontend.
- Sanitize and validate input (Zod + RHF).

## Forms
- React Hook Form + Zod (`@hookform/resolvers/zod`).

## Routing
- All routes under `src/app/`.
- Layouts stay minimal; shared chrome in `components/shared/`.
